headline: Walmart raises profit expectations as more Americans hunt deals in sluggish economy
summary: Walmart delivered another standout quarter, posting strong sales and profits that blew past Wall Street expectations as it wins over more cash-strapped Americans who have grown increasing anxious about the economy.  With other retailers dialing back projections, the nation’s largest retailer raised its financial outlook Thursday after its strong third quarter, setting itself up for a strong holiday shopping season.  Walmart Inc., based in Bentonville, Arkansas, also said Thursday that it will be transferring the listing of its common stock to the tech-heavy Nasdaq from the New York Stock Exchange.

Walmart Inc., based in Bentonville, Arkansas, also said Thursday that it will be transferring the listing of its common stock to the tech-heavy Nasdaq from the New York Stock Exchange.

headline: Walmart to Transfer Stock Exchange Listing to Nasdaq
summary: BENTONVILLE, Ark., November 20, 2025--Walmart Inc. (NYSE: WMT) today announced it will transfer the listing of its common stock to The Nasdaq Stock Market LLC (Nasdaq). The company expects its common stock to begin trading on the Nasdaq Global Select Market on December 9, 2025, under its current ticker symbol "WMT".

content.title: Walmart to Transfer Stock Exchange Listing to Nasdaq
content.summary: BENTONVILLE, Ark., November 20, 2025--Walmart Inc. (NYSE: WMT) today announced it will transfer the listing of its common stock to The Nasdaq Stock Market LLC (Nasdaq). The company expects its common stock to begin trading on the Nasdaq Global Select Market on December 9, 2025, under its current ticker symbol "WMT".

headline: Walmart Jumps to Nasdaq in Biggest Exchange Transfer on Record
summary: The Bentonville, Arkansas-based company, which has been on the NYSE since 1972, said it expects its shares to begin trading on the Nasdaq Global Select Market, the highest of the exchange’s three tiers, on Dec. 9.  The move to the tech-heavy Nasdaq reflects Walmart’s “technology-forward approach,” the retailer said, and it will transfer the listing of nine bonds to the exchange as well.  Large companies have made the move before, with PepsiCo Inc. abandoning its nearly century-long listing on the NYSE in 2017.

headline: Walmart is exploring 'every opportunity' to bring down prices: CFO
summary: Multinational retailer Walmart (WMT) raised its full-year outlook after beating third quarter earnings and revenue estimates, while warning consumers of higher prices to come due to inflation. Walmart CFO John David Rainey sits down with Market Catalysts host Julie Hyman and Yahoo Finance executive editor Brian Sozzi to talk more about the past quarter's growth, food price inflation, the items which the company is lowering prices amid tariff pressures, the chain's holiday hiring, and the company's upcoming leadership change. Walmart CEO Doug McMillon announced last week that he will be retiring from his chief executive role on January 31, 2026, to be succeeded by Walmart US CEO John Furner. summary:
STORY: Shares of Walmart rose more than six percent Thursday morning after the retail giant raised its annual forecasts for the second time this year ... following another strong quarter led by surging online sales.

Also, the company’s chief financial officer John David Rainey said on a conference call that the key holiday period is off to a good start. 

U.S. comparable sales, which combines online and store sales, rose 4.5% in the August through October period, which far exceeded estimates.

Online sales jumped 28% driven by groceries.

Walmart saw strength in discretionary categories, such as apparel and furniture as well.

The company reported gains across income brackets, with upper‑income households once again driving the strongest growth.

Rainey said spending among lower‑income households moderated, noting that, as of October, the gap in wage growth between income groups was the widest it has been in nearly a decade.

The stressed consumer environment has played to Walmart's strengths, reinforcing its role as a go-to destination not only for lower-income households but increasingly for wealthier shoppers as well.

By contrast, home improvement retailers Lowe's and Home Depot lowered their annual targets this week, blaming consumer weakness, and Target sales were also lower.

headline: Retail Earnings Send Mixed Messages About US Consumer
summary: With the earnings results from a slew of major retailers hitting, the last few days have been critical to traders seeking a view on the health of US consumers and the economy. Bloomberg Television Markets Correspondent Norah Mulinda breaks down what results from big-box chains including Target, Walmart, and Home Depot mean for the market.
